  "prompt": "Is the operation of money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, the operation of money laundering is **illegal** in virtually all jurisdictions worldwide. Money laundering involves making illegally obtained money (from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other crimes) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This process disguises the true origin of the funds.\n\n### Why is it illegal?\n1. **It facilitates criminal activity**: Money laundering enables criminals to profit from illegal activities and reinvest those profits into further criminal operations.\n2. **It undermines financial systems**: It distorts economies, fosters corruption, and erodes trust in financial institutions.\n3. **It has societal impacts**: Money laundering can fund terrorism, organized crime, and other harmful activities that destabilize societies.\n\nGovernments and international organizations, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, have established strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations to combat this practice. Individuals and organizations involved in money laundering can face severe penalties, including fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.",
